ce:section.ce:para:
Density Functional Theory (DFT) calculations were carried out by using Gaussian 09 and GaussView 5.08 program. Optimization was performed with B3LYP/6–311+g(d) level in the gas phase. The highest occupied molecular orbital energy (EHOMO
                        ) and the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital energy (ELUMO
                        ) were calculated from the optimized geometry. The theoretical HOMO/LUMO energy gap was calculated using the equation ΔEgap
                         = ELUMO - EHOMO
                        .

The Raman spectroscopy analysis of N-GQD presents intriguing insights into the structural modifications induced by N atom doping. The observation of two distinct peaks between 1200 and 1700 cm−1 corresponds to the D and G bands of N-GQD (Fig. 1b). The peak between 2100 −2500 cm−1 in the Raman spectra corresponds to the 2D band of N-GQD. The intensity ratio (ID/IG
                        ) values for DM coal were found to be 0.89. Whereas, the ID/IG
                         value of N-GQD was decreased to 0.82 which suggests the high-quality production of N-GQD (Fig. 1c) [45]. Also, the notably broader appearance of D and G bands of N-GQD than DM coal indicates the vibration of sp2 carbon materials and graphene crystalline structure [46].

The Computational study suggests that the presence of chemisorbed-N is more effective in decreasing the fermi energy level among all four states of doped N in the GQD structure (Fig. 7
                        ). The DFT calculations show the 0.0493 eV energy difference (ΔEgap
                        ) in HOMO and LUMO energy of the N-doped GQD with graphitic and pyrrolic N state (N-GQD-1, Fig. 6). This energy level is decreased to 0.04654 eV by introducing one additional pyridinic N state (N-GQD-9, Fig. 6). Interestingly, we observed the lowest HOMO and LUMO energy difference when GQD moiety contains a chemisorbed-N state along with graphitic and pyrrolic N state into the structure which is the most probable structure of our synthesized N-GQDs (N-GQD-10, Fig. 6). With the increase in graphitic and pyrrolic N with carbonyl and hydroxyl surface functionality, the HOMO-LUMO energy gap decreases. While the presence of pyridinic-N results in a high HOMO-LUMO energy difference. This phenomenon may be due to the lone pair electron of pyrrole and graphitic N involved in conjugation while the lone pair of pyridinic-N is not involved in conjugation. Our synthesized N-GQD contains less percentage of pyridinic N among other doped N states, resulting in enhanced conjugation and hence exhibiting less HOMO-LUMO energy gap (Fig. 7).
